SIMPLE: howl
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Howl
<hw>Howl</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Howled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Howling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>houlen</ets>,
<ets>hulen</ets>; akin to D. <ets>huilen</ets>, MHG. <ets>hiulen</ets>,
<ets>hiuweln</ets>, OHG. <ets>hiuwil⟦omac⟧n</ets> to exult,
<ets>h<?/wo</ets> owl, Dan. <ets>hyle</ets> to howl.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To utter a loud, protracted, mournful sound or cry, as dogs and
wolves often do.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And dogs in corners set them down to <qex>howl</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Drayton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Methought a legion of foul fiends⟦br⟧
Environ'd me about, and <qex>howled</qex> in my ears.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To utter a sound expressive of distress; to cry
aloud and mournfully; to lament; to wail.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Howl</qex> ye, for the day of the Lord is at hand.</q>
<rj><qau>Is. xiii. 6.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To make a noise resembling the cry of a wild
beast.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Wild <qex>howled</qex> the wind.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Howling monkey</b></col>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <cd>See
<er>Howler</er>, 2.</cd> -- <col><b>Howling wilderness</b></col>, <cd>a
wild, desolate place inhabited only by wild beasts.</cd> <au>Deut.
xxxii. 10.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Howl</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Howl
<hw>Howl</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To utter with outcry.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧Go . . . <xex>howl</xex> it out in deserts.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Philips.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Howl</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Howl
<hw>Howl</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The protracted, mournful
cry of a dog or a wolf, or other like sound.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A prolonged cry of distress or anguish; a
wail.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Howler</ent>⟦br⟧
